{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}
'''Archibald Gordon''', M.D. (1812–1886) was a Scottish inspector-general of hospitals.

==Life==
Gordon studied medicine at [[Edinburgh University]], where he graduated M.D. in 1834. He entered the army as assistant-surgeon in 1836, served with the 53rd regiment in the [[Sutlej campaign]] of 1846, and in the [[Punjab campaign]] of 1848-9 with the 24th regiment. He became surgeon in 1848, and surgeon-major in 1854.

In the [[Crimea War]] he was principal medical officer of the 2nd division throughout the [[Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855)|siege of Sebastopol]], and was made deputy-inspector-general of hospitals (1856), C.B., and a [[Chevalier of the Legion of Honor]]. In 1857 he served as principal medical officer with the expeditionary force to China in the [[Second Opium War]], and in the [[Oudh campaign of 1858-9]]. He became inspector-general in 1867, and retired in 1870. He was also honorary surgeon to the queen.

He died at [[West Hoathly]], Sussex, on 3 August 1886.

