{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox university | name = Rangamati Medical College | native_name = রাঙামাটি মেডিকেল কলেজ | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | other_name = <!-- or: | other_names = --> | former_name = <!-- or: | former_names = --> | established = {{start date|2014}} | academic_affiliation = [[University of Chittagong]] | type = [[Public university|Public]] [[medical school]] | principal = Prof.Dr. Md. Tipu Sultan | director = | academic_staff = 50 | administrative_staff = | students = 200(2018)<ref name=DhakaTribune>{{cite news |last=Azad |first=Abid |date=29 March 2015 |title=Rangamati Medical College reopens after two months |url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/education/2015/mar/29/rangamati-medical-college-reopens-after-two-months |newspaper=Dhaka Tribune}}</ref> | undergrad = 200 | postgrad = | doctoral = | other = | city = [[Rangamati]] | state = | country = [[Bangladesh]] | coor = {{coord|22.6578|N|92.1688|E|region:BD_type:edu|display=inline,title}} | campus = Urban | language = English | website = {{URL|rangamatimc.edu.bd}} | footnotes = }} [[File:Rangamati Medical College.jpg|thumb|Academic Building]] [[File:WP 20150617 001(1).jpg|thumb|Back View of RmMC]] '''Rangamati Medical College''' ('''RmMC''') is a [[Public university|government]] [[medical school]] in Bangladesh, established in 2014. It is located in [[Rangamati]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Uzzal |first=Moniruzzaman |date=4 August 2014 |title=Political approval alleged for 6 new med schools |url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/education/2014/aug/04/political-approval-alleged-6-new-med-schools |newspaper=Dhaka Tribune |access-date=29 November 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923225141/http://www.dhakatribune.com/education/2014/aug/04/political-approval-alleged-6-new-med-schools |archivedate=23 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It takes 51 students every year. It offers 5 years course on Bachelor of Medicine & Bachelor of Surgery which is Directed under Chittagong Medical University of Government of the People's Republic of Bangladesh.
== History == The government of Bangladesh established Rangamati Medical College in 2014, along with new medical colleges at [[Jamalpur Sadar Upazila|Jamalpur]], [[Manikganj]], [[Patuakhali]], [[Tangail]], and [[Sirajganj]].<ref>{{cite news |date=3 August 2014 |title=6 new public medical colleges to start functioning next year |url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2014/08/03/48547 |newspaper=The Financial Express |location=Dhaka}}</ref> Instruction began in January 2015,<ref name=DailyStar>{{cite news |date=9 January 2015 |title=PM opens academic activities tomorrow |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/pm-opens-academic-activities-tomorrow-58999 |newspaper=The Daily Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=11 more new govt medical colleges in country |url=http://archive.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2015/jan/11/11-more-new-govt-medical-colleges-country |newspaper=Dhaka Tribune |agency=UNB |date=11 January 2015}}</ref> with 53 students, but operations were soon suspended until the end of March as a result of vocal opposition from local groups such as [[Parbatya Chattagram Jana Samhati Samiti]] (PCJSS).<ref name=DhakaTribune /> The groups believe that students, staff, and faculty would come predominantly from outside the [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]], and their settlement in Rangamati would change the character of the region.<ref>{{cite news |title=Govt disregarding CHT accord: Santu Larma |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/govt-disregarding-cht-accord-santu-larma-33399 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=15 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Chakma |first=Mangal Kumar |date=19 January 2015 |title=Why a medical college at Rangamati? |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/why-a-medical-college-at-rangamati-60566 |newspaper=The Daily Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bangladesh govt asked to declare road map or face movement |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/declare-road-map-or-face-movement-181549 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=3 December 2015}}</ref>
==Campus== The college is located in [[Rangamati]], headquarters of [[Rangamati Hill District]]. It's temporary campus is within the premises of Rangamati General Hospital.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rangamatimc.edu.bd/ |title=Welcome to Rangamati Medical College |website=Rangamati Medical College |access-date=10 January 2017}}</ref>
==Organization and administration== The college is affiliated with [[Chittagong University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cu.ac.bd/ctguni/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=80&Itemid=191 |title=Affiliated Colleges |website=University of Chittagong |access-date=7 September 2015}}</ref> The students receive their MBBS degree under the [[University of Chittagong]] after completing 5th year course of study by passing the final professional MBBS examination.
This college is directly governed by [[Bangladesh Medical and Dental Council]] (BMDC) – an affiliation of the [[Ministry of health]]. The professional examinations are held under the university and results are given thereby. Internal examinations are also taken on regular intervals namely items, card completions, terms end and regular assessments.
==Academics== The admission process of undergraduate MBBS course for all government medical colleges in Bangladesh is conducted centrally by the Director of Medical Education under DGHS under the [[Ministry of health]]. The test comprises a written MCQ exam, which is held simultaneously in all government medical colleges on the same day throughout the country. Candidates are selected for admission based on national merit and district, whether they are sons or daughters of freedom fighters, and to fill tribal quotas. For foreign students, admission is through the embassy of Bangladesh in their respective countries. The academic calendar for different years is maintained by respective departments. The admission test consists of the written MCQ exam.
